One of our amazing teachers, Suzanne Harris, has been nominated for a 2020 CARE Award! Now it's up to you to help make Suzanne an award winner!

BSD Education hosts the CARE Awards as a way to recognize some of the hard-working teachers who are making a real impact in the lives of their students. Nominees represent a diverse group of teachers that exemplify one or more of BSD's four foundational characteristics: Curious, Adaptable, Resilient, and Empathetic.

Voting closes Saturday, so please make sure to vote and share!

http://bsd.education/care-awards/

post_text:
Some students from our Arts and Sciences campus had an opportunity to brighten up the airport with their work! The work from students in Leah Uniacke and Jenna Kurczewski's art classes can be found at A-East Baggage Claim in the Philadelphia Airport. The exhibition is called "The Color of Us". The exhibition features portraits and geography-based themes by students in 5th-8th grade. The various techniques include drawing, painting, collage, and printmaking using mediums from acrylic, watercolor, tempera to marker and glitter.

If you are traveling, make sure to go find this exhibition. And if you have no plans to travel, make sure to share this post to spread some joy and appreciation for our students.

SEE IT. REPORT IT.
Safe2Say Something is a school safety tool that will save lives.

Safe2Say Something is a youth violence prevention program run by the Pennsylvania Office of Attorney General. The program teaches youth and adults how to recognize warning signs and signals, especially within social media, from individuals who may be a threat to themselves or others and to “say something” BEFORE it is too late.

https://www.safe2saypa.org

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS!!! Techno Knights advance to the State Championship... On Saturday, three of our four robotics teams went to the Philadelphia qualifier for FIRST Tech Challenge. This was their 1st time competing at this type of competition. At this qualifier for the state championships, 25 teams were competing. We started getting our robot together in November and were very happy just to make it to the competition. Our predominantly sophomore team, The Techno Knights, stole the show by winning all 5 of their matches and advanced to finals. They also won the Design Award and was the 4th and final team from the qualifier to advance to the State Championships in York, Pa. Team Lil’Boat also left with hardware by winning the Rockwell Collins Innovate Award. Blue Bot had a great competition as well and we were all excited and inspired by competing at this level.

The Philadelphia Orchestra String Quartet performed at the Vine Street Campus of Philadelphia Performing Arts: A String Theory Charter School yesterday. This was part of The Philadelphia Orchestra's "We're HEAR week" that has musicians performing in community-base concerts throughout the city. This concert was special to our community as Isabel Morales, one of our middle school cello players, was able to watch her mom Dara Morales (violinist in the 2nd violin section of The Phila. Orchestra-POA) and her Aunt Amy Oshiro-Morales (violinist with the orchestra as well) perform at her school.

Thank you to The Philadelphia Orchestra for performing!

Who said school can't be fun?!

All of the Staff from all String Theory Schools were at the Vine Street Campus on Tuesday for Professional Development. If you enjoyed the performance give the video a like and a share!

Stay tuned for String Theory Schools Staff School Spirit Video of "You Can't Stop The Beat", featuring all of our teachers and staff! And don't miss the String Theory Players performances of Hairspray, coming this fall!

post_text:
Students from Philadelphia Performing Arts were invited to participate in the recording session for a new album called Peace and Love. They sang “Get Together” with TJP (formerly The Jost Project.) Paul Jost conducted them and their voices were added to the track with Paul (vocal, harmonica), Tony Miceli (vibes), Kevin MacConnell (bass), Doug Hirlinger (drums) and special guest on the album Joel Frahm (saxophone.)

Here is a short segment with a most important message for today – Come on people now, smile on your brother, everybody get together … ! We hope you’ll share it!

Peace and Love (Dot Time Records) was recording at Hamilton Soundworks in Germantown and will be released later in the fall, 2017.

If you enjoyed this, make sure to share!

This video below demonstrates many images of peace created to promote Peace Day Philly (Sept. 17 to Sept. 23) with a musical backdrop that includes the chorus from Philadelphia Performing Arts! It’s from the new album coming out in September called “Peace and Love” (Dot Time Records) by The Jost Project, a local band who performs worldwide. Our students join Paul Jost-vocals, Tony Miceli-vibes, Kevin MacConnell-bass, Doug Hirlinger-drums and Joel Frahm-saxophone -- on a song medley “Waters of March/Get Together.” The band hopes to visit us on Monday, Sept. 18 at 10 a.m. to launch their CD, sing with our students on the album and welcome the founder of Peace Day Philly, Lisa Parker.

post_text: This week we have 5 exchange students from Kobe, Japan visiting us and staying with our students and their families. They have toured the city, taken classes with our students, enjoyed our production of Annie, had a reception at Mayor Kenney's office, visited Temple University, and will visit the Art Museum tomorrow before heading home. Today, Vice Mayor of Kobe, Toshiro Tamada visited our school and enjoyed the presentation our visiting students gave to our French classes.

"Please join us for our second annual Family Science Night, featuring the 6th and 7th grade STEM majors! We have two evenings planned of hands-on experiments and scientific activities that students and their families can do together. The best part of the evening, is that all activities are provided and run by our very own 6th and 7th graders! Our evenings take place on Wednesday, November 2nd with out 6th grade student facilitators, and on Thursday, November 3rd with our 7th grade student facilitators. Both evenings run from 6pm to 8pm. Any questions can be directed to Ms. Luccioni at nluccioni@stringtheoryschools.org (Vine St.), Mr. Mecca at cmeccariello@stringtheoryschools.org (West), or Ms. Miller at mmiller@stringtheoryschools.org (East)."

post_text: String Theory Schools is hosting session one of a CreativeXchange workshop for The Arts and Business Council of Greater Philadelphia. Participants interact with some of Philadelphia’s top creative minds and investigate several techniques that instructors use to cultivate a sense of innovation in their work. Our TV and Broadcasting Majors are taping the whole event, editing the video to be used by the Arts and Business Council. Students will remain with the group for the whole workshop.

post_text:
***

Philadelphia Performing Arts is starting a NEW Drone Racing Team as an after school club this school year. If the thought of flying quadcopters around tight corners, hurling down narrow straightaways and jostling for position against other racers thrills you, this may be the after school club for you! There will be two teams to try out for, Varsity and Junior Varsity. Varsity will consist of flying faster, larger quadcopters outdoors and Junior Varsity will fly smaller quadcopters indoors. Come join us in making history! Are you curious to see what it may look like? Watch “Drone Racing - The Sport of The Future” at https://youtu.be/bOWkkoczEPQ.

Meetings are Tuesdays & Thursdays after school
Vine Street Theater
Ages: Open to all students 5th-12th grade
Contact: droneracing@stringtheoryschools.org

Philadelphia Performing Arts now has six resident companies on the 8th floor of the Vine Street Campus! Today the High School staff met with the company founders to begin collaboration and dream up unbelievable projects for this upcoming school year. These six companies have committed to working with students, collaborating with our teachers, providing internships, and giving students a front seat view of a start up company!
